Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)

As I mentioned in my previous comments, I don't think 50 is a bad number to start with. Until we know more about the scenarios this will be used in, we can't estimate that number correctly.

We ought to be conservative but we shouldn't make it useless by being over-conservative. Therefore, I think 50 is a good sane default for now. The number was not taken from any math so it's not empirically generated but it's not way too low (like 2) nor way too high (like 1000).

16:40:46 [ nikhil_k] flaper87: hey, Rackspace public cloud uses tasks on production systems
16:41:04 [ nikhil_k] so based on that I can say that the operations can be really expensive if on the API node

Patch Set 8:

So, the way it's setup in a production system:

One sema for 2 types of tasks. The max# tasks can be queued up (disruptive by deploy) are 1000 (same as #workers threads on a single Glance API process).

However, the sema ensures that only one can run at a time. This is important as an expensive operation on Disk (when task is run on the API node) can result into 503s for the user.

Having said that, the defaults can be greater for non-API nodes. We need to better educate the operators to set up their infrastructure for setting high defaults on non-API nodes. So, if we can keep them to very low 2, 4 or max 10; that would be great.
